## Project 2 — Customer Base Audit

**Folder:** `Customer-Base-Audit`

### Overview

Price distribution analysis of 41 customer transactions, ranging from $135 to $628. The dataset was organized into a frequency distribution to identify dominant price segments and formulate evidence-based managerial recommendations.

### Methods Applied

- Data cleaning and preparation in Microsoft Excel
- Frequency distribution construction using equal-width intervals ($100 width)
- Relative frequency and cumulative frequency calculations using COUNTIF formulas
- Histogram construction to visualize distribution shape
- Interpretation of distribution skewness and customer segmentation

### Key Results

| Price Range | Frequency | Relative Frequency | Cumulative % |
|-------------|-----------|-------------------|--------------|
| $100 – $199 | 8         | 19.51%            | 19.51%       |
| $200 – $299 | 15        | 36.59%            | 56.10%       |
| $300 – $399 | 9         | 21.95%            | 78.05%       |
| $400 – $499 | 5         | 12.20%            | 90.24%       |
| $500 – $599 | 3         | 7.32%             | 97.56%       |
| $600 – $700 | 1         | 2.44%             | 100.00%      |
| **Total**   | **41**    | **100.00%**       |              |

The distribution is **positively skewed**. The $200–$299 segment is the dominant price bracket, accounting for 36.6% of all transactions. The lower two segments ($100–$299) together represent 56.1% of the customer base.

